{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492391"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:27:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1045"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1045"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.27,0,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1045"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89120"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39419"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old woman attends her general practitioner for a routine health check. Her main health issue is chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and she finds that she has difficulty moving about the house because of her breathing problems and cannot climb stairs. Her medications include perindopril for hypertension, paracetamol for osteoarthritis and tiotropium. A maternal aunt was diagnosed with carcinoma of the colon at the age of 65. There is no other family history of bowel cancer and the patient wonders if she needs to take any action. She has no digestive tract symptoms and she has never been part of any screening program.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further action needs to be taken","Biennial faecal occult blood testing","Flexible sigmoidoscopy","Colonoscopy","CT colonography"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECurrent recommendations are that routine screening should be tailored in patients between the ages of 75 - 85. The fit patient in this age group with few co-morbidities could be considered for a screening test and the faecal occult blood test is the less intrusive or risky. If this test is positive, a colonoscopy could be considered. The question to be asked is \u0027what action would be taken if a cancer was found on screening?\u0027 If the answer is \u0027no action\u0027 - then screening should not be undertaken in the first place. This patient has a significant co-morbidity in terms of her chronic lung disease - and it is most unlikely that any definitive action would be taken if she did have a serious colonic problem. \u003Cstrong\u003ENo further action needs to be taken\u003C/strong\u003E in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Screening in the older groups of patients needs to be matched against the general state of health of the individual."],"references":["Rex DK, Boland R, Dominitz JA, et al. Colorectal Cancer Screening: Recommendations for Physicians and Patients from the U.S. Multi-Society Task Force on Colorectal Cancer. Am J Gastroenterol 2017; 112:1016-30."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89120"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1045"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89120","links":{"self":"